Common Denominator Principle
=============================
All observables are different transfer functions of the same
underlying structures: Δρ, M_{2,3}, K(θ), Π.

Therefore a single global likelihood can be written:

    L(𝒑) = L_TT(𝒑) × L_ϕ(𝒑) × L_TB/EB(𝒑) × L_pol(𝒑) × L_ACT/SPT(𝒑)

Key advantage:

  • Parameters are tightly cross-linked, not independent.
  • A_Q, A_D set low-ℓ TT, then fix α₁, α₂ via (k_Q, k_D),
    and feed TB/EB via (γ_Π, ε_Π), all with the same axis û.


Relaxed Hierarchical Module
=============================
RCG doesn’t require a single rigid global fit of the full CDP vector. 


                     RCG — STRUCTURED FLEXIBILITY OPTIONS 
-------------------   --------------------------------------------   -------------------------------
Approach              Description                                   When to Use
-------------------   --------------------------------------------   -------------------------------
Strict Global Fit     One single vector 𝒑 constrained by all        Best-case scenario; strongest
                      datasets simultaneously.                       confirmation of unified RCG.

Sector-wise           Split 𝒑 into sub-vectors:                     When one sector is poorly
                      {geom, boundary, lensing, chiral}.             constrained or noisy.

Hierarchical Fitting  Step 1: Fit low-ℓ TT + lensing → fix          Most practical starting point;
                      {μ, ν, α, d₀, A_Q, A_D, û, k_Q, k_D}.          preserves predictive structure.
                      Step 2: Add chiral sector.

Relaxed Closures      Allow perturbative decoupling (e.g.,          If TB/EB tension appears or
                      ε_Π not strictly tied to A_Q).                 chiral sector needs freedom.

Effective Parameters  Absorb mismatches into effective              Intermediate step before full
                      {k_Q, k_D, γ_Π} within bounds.                 revision; diagnostic tool.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Risk / Trade-off
----------------
Strict Global Fit     High risk of tension; may overconstrain model.
Sector-wise           Loses some predictive power; weaker cross-links.
Hierarchical Fitting  Requires careful propagation of uncertainties.
Relaxed Closures      Reduces elegance; increases model complexity.
Effective Parameters  Can hide deeper structural issues if overused.
================================================================================	

Strategy
========
Stage 1 (Core): 
Fit low-ℓ TT + Planck lensing
→ Fix p_geom + p_boundary + p_lensing = {μ, ν, α, d₀, A_Q, A_D, û, k_Q, k_D}

Stage 2 (Chiral test): 
Using the fixed core, predict γ_Π and ε_Π range and confront with TB/EB + polarization
→ Either:
It fits naturally 	→ strong success
It needs relaxation 	→ introduce a chiral decoupling factor (e.g. f_chiral ∈ [0.5, 2.0])

Stage 3 (Cross-check): 
Use ACT/SPT lensing + full polarization maps as independent validation.

